@node Introduction
@chapter Introduction

You keep a weekly plan as an org table. Each row is a time block, each
column after the first is a day, and each filled cell holds a letter (A,
B, C, or D) that names the project worked on during that block. This
package reads that table and writes a dated file of events for each
week, so past weeks are archived rather than overwritten. Those events
feed the org agenda, and org's own iCalendar exporter turns them into a
file that Outlook Web or any calendar application can import.

The table is a seating chart. You decide who sits where, meaning which
project fills which block. The generator is the usher that walks the
chart, stamps each seat with a real date and time, and hands the guest
list to your calendar.

@cindex related work
The package @code{org-timeblock} gives org-agenda an interactive
timeblock view of scheduled tasks. This package is complementary,
because it generates and archives a week from a reusable template and
exports it to iCalendar, rather than viewing timestamps that already
exist, so the two pair well.

@node Installation
@chapter Installation

Place @file{writing-schedule.el} on your load path and require it.

@lisp
(add-to-list 'load-path "~/path/to/writing-schedule")
(require 'writing-schedule)

;; Where the dated weekly files are archived.
(setq writing-schedule-directory "~/org/writing-schedule/")

;; A timezone string keeps exported events anchored correctly.
(setq org-icalendar-timezone "America/Chicago")
@end lisp

The package depends only on Emacs 27.1 or later and on the built-in
@code{org} and @code{ox-icalendar} libraries. No external packages are
required to generate schedules or export calendars.

@node The Table Format
@chapter The Table Format

A schedule table has one label column and one column per day. The first
row names the days. Section header rows group the blocks. Time-block
rows carry a time range in the label column and a project letter in each
day cell that is in use. Legend rows at the bottom associate each letter
with a description.

@example
| Time <l>    | M | Tu | W | Th | F | Sa |
|-------------+---+----+---+----+---+----|
| Generative: |   |    |   |    |   |    |
| 04:00-05:30 | A | B  | A | B  | B |    |
| 05:45-07:15 | A | B  | A | B  | B | B  |
|-------------+---+----+---+----+---+----|
| A:          |   |    |   |    |   |    |
| B:          |   |    |   |    |   |    |
@end example

The parser is tolerant of irregular spacing and of single-digit hours,
so @samp{9:15 - 10:45} and @samp{04:00-5:30} are both accepted. A cell
letter may be lower case; it is normalized to upper case. An empty cell
means that no block is scheduled for that day and time.

@node Commands
@chapter Commands

@deffn Command writing-schedule-insert-template n
Insert a blank weekly table for @var{n} projects, where @var{n} is
clamped to the range one to four. The default time blocks come from
@code{writing-schedule-default-slots}.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-generate
Parse the table at point and write the schedule file. For each letter in
use, you are prompted for a project code and a description. When the
legend rows carry a description, it is offered as the default. You then
pick any day inside the target week, and the command snaps back to that
week's Monday. The command writes a dated file for that week, such as
@file{writing-2026-01-19.org}, inside @code{writing-schedule-directory},
optionally adds it to @code{org-agenda-files}, and offers to export an
iCalendar file.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-export-ics &optional file
Export @var{file}, or the current week's dated file when @var{file} is
omitted, to an iCalendar file through org's @code{ox-icalendar} back-end.
The @file{.ics} file is written beside the org file, so it is archived by
week as well. Return the absolute path of the resulting file.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-add-to-agenda &optional file
Add @var{file}, or the current week's dated file when @var{file} is
omitted, to @code{org-agenda-files}. The operation is idempotent.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-open-week &optional pick-date
Open an archived weekly file. By default, choose from the archived weeks
with completion, listed newest first, so a recent week is quick to reach.
With a prefix argument @var{pick-date}, or when nothing is archived yet,
prompt for a date instead and open the file for the week that contains
it.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-open-recent
Open the most recent archived weekly file.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-new-week-from-template
Start the current week from a saved context template. Choose a template
from @code{writing-schedule-template-directory}, copy it to this week's
working table in @code{writing-schedule-table-directory}, open that copy,
and place point in the table so you can run
@code{writing-schedule-generate} right away. The copy is separate from
the template, so the library stays intact.
@end deffn

@node Customization
@chapter Customization

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-directory
The directory that holds one dated schedule file per week. Each
generated week is archived here under its own file.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-file-format
The format of a weekly file name. The @samp{%s} is replaced by the
Monday of the week in ISO form, giving a file such as
@file{writing-2026-01-19.org}. The default is @code{"writing-%s.org"}.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-template-directory
The directory of saved context templates, each an org file whose table
already has the letters assigned. The default is a @file{templates}
subdirectory of @code{writing-schedule-directory}.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-table-directory
The directory where @code{writing-schedule-new-week-from-template} copies
this week's working table. The default is a @file{tables} subdirectory of
@code{writing-schedule-directory}, which keeps input tables out of the
way of the dated schedules and the agenda.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-use-todo
When non-nil, each generated event is a TODO headline, so the schedule
file also serves as a source of TODO items. Set it to nil for cleaner
iCalendar summaries. The default is @code{t}.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-todo-keyword
The keyword placed before each event when
@code{writing-schedule-use-todo} is non-nil. The default is @code{"TODO"}.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-add-to-agenda
When non-nil, each generated dated file is added to
@code{org-agenda-files}. The default is @code{t}.
@end defvr

@defvr {User Option} writing-schedule-default-slots
The sections and time blocks used by
@code{writing-schedule-insert-template}. Each element is a list whose
head is a section name and whose tail is a list of time ranges.
@end defvr

@node Key Bindings
@chapter Key Bindings

The package ships a prefix keymap that puts the commands on single keys.

@defvr {Variable} writing-schedule-command-map
A keymap binding @kbd{g} to @code{writing-schedule-generate}, @kbd{t} to
@code{writing-schedule-insert-template}, @kbd{o} to
@code{writing-schedule-open-week}, @kbd{r} to
@code{writing-schedule-open-recent}, @kbd{n} to
@code{writing-schedule-new-week-from-template}, @kbd{e} to
@code{writing-schedule-export-ics}, and @kbd{a} to
@code{writing-schedule-add-to-agenda}.
@end defvr

Bind it under any prefix you like. When @kbd{C-c w} is already your
writing prefix, nest it on a free key such as @kbd{c}.

@lisp
(with-eval-after-load 'writing-schedule
  (keymap-set my-writing-prefix "c" writing-schedule-command-map))
@end lisp

After that, @kbd{C-c w c r} opens the most recent week, and
@kbd{C-c w c o} opens a week by completion or, with a prefix argument, by
date.

@node Calendar Sync
@chapter Calendar Sync

Because the generated file holds ordinary org headlines with active
timestamps, org's iCalendar exporter turns each block into a timed
event. Run @code{writing-schedule-export-ics} to write the file, then
import it into Outlook Web through @emph{Add calendar} and @emph{Upload
from file}. The exporter writes a stable identifier into each headline,
so re-importing an edited week updates the matching events rather than
creating duplicates.

To feed the agenda, add your task file, the archive directory
@code{writing-schedule-directory}, and any project writing logs to
@code{org-agenda-files}. Pointing the agenda at the directory picks up
every dated week automatically, so all of them act as sources of TODO
items and timed blocks.

@node Command Line
@chapter Command Line

People who do not use Emacs can still produce a calendar from a template.
The @file{writing-schedule.sh} script uses Emacs only as an engine and
writes an iCalendar file for import into Apple Calendar or Outlook.

@example
./writing-schedule.sh list
./writing-schedule.sh generate three-projects 2026-01-21
./writing-schedule.sh deps
@end example

The @code{list} command prints the available templates. The
@code{generate} command writes a dated schedule and an @file{.ics} file
for the week that contains the given date. Paths are configured through
the environment variables @env{WS_DIR}, @env{WS_TEMPLATE_DIR},
@env{WS_OUT_DIR}, and @env{WS_TIMEZONE}. The script drives the two batch
functions below, which can also be called directly through
@command{emacs --batch}.

@deffn Command writing-schedule-batch-list-templates &optional directory
Print the available templates to standard output, one per line.
@var{directory} defaults to @code{writing-schedule-template-directory}.
@end deffn

@deffn Command writing-schedule-batch-generate table week &optional out-dir
Generate a dated schedule and an iCalendar file from @var{table} for the
week that contains @var{week}. Letters are mapped to projects from the
table's legend rows, so no prompts are needed. @var{out-dir} overrides
@code{writing-schedule-directory}. For readable event titles, fill the
legend rows of the template, because those descriptions become the event
titles.
@end deffn

@node Testing
@chapter Testing

The package ships with an ERT test suite split into unit tests and
integration tests, plus a Makefile. Run the whole suite with:

@example
make test
@end example

Run only one layer with @code{make test-unit} or
@code{make test-integration}. Measure line coverage with
@code{make coverage} after installing the test dependencies through
@code{make install-test-deps}. See @file{README.md} for the full
testing tutorial.

